fession   = [[Lawyer]]<br/>[[Judge]]<br/>[[Politician]]\n| residence    = [[Tyler, Texas]]\n| branch       = [[United States Army]]\n| serviceyears = 1978\u20131982\n| rank         = [[File:US military captain's rank.gif|25px]] [[Captain (United States)#U.S. Army, Air Force, and Marine Corps|Captain]]<ref name=\"AUSA2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ausa.org/legislation/congressionalinfo/Documents/OAS%20112th%20Congress.pdf|title=Once a Soldier... Always a Soldier|author=Staff|year=2011|work=Legislative Agenda|publisher=[[Association of the United States Army]]|accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref>\n| unit         = [[Judge Advocate General's Corps (United States Army)|Judge Advocate General's Corps]]\n| awards       = [[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]]<ref name=\"AUSA2011\"/>}}\n\n'''Louis Buller \"Louie\" Gohmert, Jr.''' (born August 18, 1953) is an American politician and current [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Texas]]'s [[Texas's 1st congressional district|First Congressional District]].\n\n==Early life, education, and early political career==\nGohmert was born in [[Pittsburg, Texas]], the son of Erma Sue (n\u00e9e Brooks) and Louis Buller Gohmert. He is of German descent on his father's side.<ref name=frpg1>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/gohmert.htm|title=Louis Buller \"Louie\" Gohmert, Jr.|publisher=ancestry.com|date=April 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/members/19262.html|title=Rep. Louie Gohmert (R-Texas)|publisher=rollcall.com|date=April 8, 2013}}</ref> Gohmert was raised in [[Mount Pleasant, Texas]], where he graduated from [[Mount Pleasant High School (Texas)|the local high school]] in 1971.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/members/G000552|title=The U.S. Congress Votes Data Base: Louie Gohmert (R-TX)|publisher=washingtonpost.com}}</ref> He was then accepted into [[Texas A&M University]], receiving his [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[history]] in 1975.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/elections/2004/candidates/22273|title=Louie B. Gohmert (R)|publisher=washingtonpost.com|date=June 30, 2004}}</ref>\n\nGohmert spent a summer as an exchange student in [[Ukraine]].<ref>[http://www.frontpagemag.com/2014/frontpagemag-com/rep-louie-gohmert-american-strength-is-security Rep. Louie Gohmert: American Strength is Security], frontpagemag.com; accessed August 24, 2014.</ref> He received an [[United States Army|army]] scholarship while at Texas A&M, where he was a brigade commander of the [[Texas A&M University Corps of Cadets|Corps of Cadets]] and class president.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2010/memberdistrict/188|title=NationalJournalAlmanac Texas District 1 Rep. Louie Gohmert (R)|publisher=nationaljournal.com|date=April 8, 2013}}</ref> He later received his [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Baylor Law School]] in [[Waco, Texas]] in 1977 where he was class president.<ref name=\"The Wall Street Journal\">{{cite news|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/louie-gohmert--TX-H|title=Louie Gohmert (R)|author=''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''|publisher=wsj.com}}</ref>\n\nGohmert served in the [[United States Army]] [[Judge Advocate General's Corps, United States Army|Judge Advocate General's Corps]], at [[Fort Benning, Georgia]], from 1978-82.<ref name=\"Houston Chronicle\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.chron.com/txpotomac/2010/07/texas-delegation-in-depth-louie-gohmert|title=Texas delegation in depth: Louie Gohmert|author=''[[Houston Chronicle]]''|publisher=chron.com|date=July 1, 2010}}</ref> The majority of his U.S. Army legal service was as a defense attorney.\n\nGohmert was elected as a state district judge for Texas's 7th Judicial District, serving [[Smith County, Texas|Smith County]] ([[Tyler, Texas]]) from 1992 to 2002; being reelected to a total of three terms.<ref name=\"Houston Chronicle\"/> Gohmert first saw national recognition for a 1996 probation requirement where he ordered an [[H.I.V.]] positive man, who was convicted on [[motor vehicle theft]] charges, to seek the written consent from all future sexual partners on a court provided form notifying them of his H.I.V. status;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/26/us/louie-gohmert-texas-republican-notorious-yet-popular.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=nytimes.com|author=Jay Root|date=August 26, 2012|work=The New York Times}}</ref> angering LGBT activists and civil libertarians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texastribune.org/2012/08/26/courting-controversy-works-gohmert|title=Courting Controversy Works for Louie Gohmert|author=Jay Root|publisher=''[[The Texas Tribune]]''|date=August 26, 2012}}</ref> Gohmert was appointed by [[Governor of Texas|Texas Governor]] [[Rick Perry]] to fill a vacancy as Chief Justice on Texas's 12th Court of Appeals, where he served a six month term from 2002 to 2003.<ref name=\"The Wall Street Journal\"/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\nA mid-decade redistricting made the 1st District significantly more Republican than its predecessor, notably by moving Gohmert's home in Tyler from the 4th to the 1st. In the Republican primary, Gohmert defeated [[Texas House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Wayne Christian]] of [[Center, Texas|Center]], who thereafter returned to the state legislature but was unseated in the 2012 Republican primary. Gohmert defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent 1st District Congressman [[Max Sandlin]] with 61 percent of the vote to Sandlin's 39 percent, becoming the first Republican since [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]] to represent northeast Texas.\n\nProving just how Republican this district was, Gohmert has been elected four times with virtually no opposition. In 2006, Gohmert won his second term by defeating Democrat Roger L. Owen, a [[swimming pool]] builder from [[Hallsville, Texas]]. He faced no major party opposition in 2008 or 2010.\n\nOn November 6, 2012, Gohmert was elected to his fifth term with 182,621 votes (71.7 percent) to the Democrat Shirley J. McKellar's 67,758 (26.6 percent). The [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] Clark Patterson polled the remaining 1.6 percent of the ballots.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/nov06_164_state.htm?x=0&y=674&id=976|title=General election returns, November 6, 2012|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=November 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nFrom January 2005 to October 2013, Gohmert missed 551 of 6,900 roll call votes, which is 8.0%. The median number of such votes missed is 2.3%.\n[[File:David Dykes Invocation Photo Op.jpg|thumb|R-L: House Chaplain \n\n[[Daniel P. Coughlin]] presents pastor [[David O. Dykes|David Dykes]] a certificate in honor of his September 10, 2008 Invocation of the US House, while Gohmert and Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] stand by.]]\nIn 2007 Gohmert said, \"I would submit to you that [[Washington, D.C.]] is also the only city in the entire country that every Senator and every Member of Congress has a vested interest in seeing that it works properly, that water works, sewer works, and no other city in America has that.\"<ref>http://dcist.com/2007/03/23/meet_your_new_r.php</ref> When residents began calling Gohmert's office complaining about issues like trash and parking, he told them to speak to local government officials instead.<ref>{{cite web|author=Martin Austermuhle|url=http://dcist.com/2012/05/take_your_constituent_concerns_to_c.php|title=Take Your Constituent Concerns to Congress Tomorrow|publisher=DCist|date=2012-05-22|accessdate=2014-08-08}}</ref> Washington, D.C. has been described as a modern example of [[virtual representation]], although it has no voting representatives in Congress. {{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nOn July 29, 2009, he signed on as a co-sponsor of the defeated [[H.R. 1503]]. This bill would have amended \"the Federal Election Campaign Act of 1971 to require the principal campaign committee of a candidate for election to the office of president to include with the committee's statement of organization a copy of the candidate's birth certificate, together with such other documentation as may be necessary to establish that the candidate meets the qualifications for eligibility to the office of president under the Constitution\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opencongress.org/bill/111-h1503/text|title=Text of H.R.1503 as Introduced in House: Presidential Eligibility Act&nbsp;\u2013 U.S. Congress|publisher=OpenCongress|date=March 12, 2009|accessdate=September 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nGohmert stated in a House Judiciary Hearing on May 15, 2013, that he believed the FBI did not act with due diligence concerning alleged bomber [[Tamerlan Tsarnaev]]. His contention was that the FBI was more interested in Christian groups such as those led by [[Billy Graham|Billy]] and [[Franklin Graham]] than in groups that might be considered less politically correct to target. Attorney General [[Eric Holder]] responded to his claims: \"The only observation I was going to make is that you state as a matter of fact what the FBI did and did not do. Unless somebody has done something inappropriate, you don't have access to the FBI files ... I know what the FBI did. You cannot know what I know. That's all\". Gohmert objected to this on the grounds that Holder had \"challenge[d]\" his character and made several unsuccessful attempts to inject his viewpoint as a point of personal privilege.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2014/04/08/300612766/holder-plays-asparagus-card-against-gop-antagonist|title=Louie Gohmert Goes Off On Eric Holder At House Hearing|publisher=NPR|date=April 8, 2014|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn January 3, 2013, Gohmert broke ranks with the House leadership to nominate outspoken Florida Representative [[Allen West (politician)|Allen West]] for [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]], although West narrowly lost his bid for re-election in November 2012, and was no longer a member of Congress.<ref>Chris Moody (January 3, 2013), [http://news.yahoo.com/blogs/ticket/john-boehner-elected-speaker-house-190301689--politics.html \"John Boehner re-elected as speaker of the House\"], ''[[Yahoo News]]''; accessed August 24, 2014.</ref>\n\nAlthough he has previously ruled out the possibility of a bid for the U.S. Senate, he has recently been boosted by at least one \"tea party\" group (Grassroots America We the People) as a primary challenger to current Republican Senator [[John Cornyn]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Texas Tea Partyers want Louie Gohmert for Senate|author=Rayfield, J.|url=http://www.salon.com/2013/08/08/texas_tea_partiers_want_louie_gohmert_for_senate/singleton|newspaper=Salon|date=August 8, 2013|accessdate=August 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Fiscal policy====\nGohmert has signed the [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge|Americans for Tax Reform]]'s [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge]].<ref name=\"ATR\">{{cite web|title=The Taxpayer Protection Pledge Signers 112th Congressional List|url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/atrfiles/files/files/091411-federalpledgesigners.pdf|publisher=Americans for Tax Reform|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> Gohmert offered an alternative plan to kick-start the economy with his tax holiday bill that would allow taxpayers to be exempt for two months from having federal income tax taken out of their paychecks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,459525,00.html|work=Fox News|title=Rep. Louie Gohmert Wants Congress to Ditch Federal Income tax for 2008|date=December 1, 2008}}</ref> Gohmert was one of a number of Republicans who voted against the [[Budget Control Act of 2011]] on grounds it did not do enough to deal with the government's growing debt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=31558116&category=views&id=140971302572 |title=Louie Gohmert&nbsp;\u2013 Debt, Deficit, Spending, and the Size of Government |publisher=The Political Guide|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref> Gohmert was one of four Republicans who voted against, joining 161 Democrats to oppose a balanced budget Constitutional amendment in November 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=House rejects balanced budget amendment|agency=Associated Press|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/washington/story/2011-11-18/balanced-budget-amendment-house-vote/51297960/1|newspaper=USA Today|date=November 18, 2011|accessdate=December 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGohmert does not believe in man made climate change, and has asserted that data supporting the theory is [http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/Profiles/House/Texas/Louie_Gohmert/Views/Energy_and_the_Environment fraudulent]. He opposes cap-and-trade legislation, such as the one that was passed in the US House when it was Democratic controlled, and supports expanding drilling, and exploration and drilling in Arctic National Wildlife Refuge (ANWR).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=31558116&category=views&id=20100506145376|title=Louie Gohmert&nbsp;\u2013 Energy and the Environment|publisher=The Political Guide|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2012 meeting of the [[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|House Natural Resources Committee]], Gohmert stated his strong support of a [[Trans-Alaska Pipeline System|trans-Alaskan pipeline]], as a means for [[caribou]] to have more sex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adn.com/2012/02/07/2304478/texas-congressman-lectures-colleagues.html|title=Texas congressman lectures colleagues on caribou romance|publisher=Anchorage Daily News|date=February 7, 2012|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/the-state-department-is-no-donald-trump/2012/02/07/gIQANuCkyQ_story.html|work=The Washington Post|first=Al|last=Kamen|title=The State Department is no Donald Trump|date=February 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lushing|first=Dustin|url=http://www.newser.com/story/139284/things-congress-talks-about-caribou-sex.html|title=Things Congress Talks About: Caribou Sex&nbsp;\u2013 Texas' Louie Gohmert says Alaskan pipeline is hot date meet-up|publisher=Newser|date=February 8, 2012|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref> According to Gohmert, \"When [the caribou] want to go on a date, they invite each other to head over to the pipeline. So [his] real concern now [is] ... if oil stops running through the pipeline ... do we need a study to see how adversely the caribou would be affected if that warm oil ever quit flowing?\u201d {{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nGohmert's comments were not favorably received by the rest of the committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/192125/texas-republican-supports-pipeline-for-the-sake-of-caribou-sex|title=Texas Republican Supports Pipeline For The Sake Of Caribou Sex|publisher=The Inquisitr|date=February 8, 2012|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/in-the-loop/post/louie-gohmert-best-caribou-wingman-ever/2012/02/07/gIQAIj2dwQ_blog.html|work=The Washington Post|first=Emily|last=Heil|title=Louie Gohmert: Best caribou wingman ever|date=February 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nGohmert has stated his support for and voted for legislation in favor of [[school voucher]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=31558116&category=views&id=20100527128545|title=Louie Gohmert&nbsp;\u2013 Education|publisher=The Political Guide|accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe strongly supported the [[Baseline Reform Act of 2013 (H.R. 1871; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would change the way in which discretionary [[Appropriations bill (United States)|appropriations]] for individual accounts are projected in CBO\u2019s [[Baseline (budgeting)|baseline]].<ref name=\"cbo1871\"/> Under H.R. 1871, projections of such spending would still be based on the current year\u2019s appropriations, but would not be adjusted for [[inflation]] going forward.<ref name=cbo1871>{{cite web|title=CBO - H.R. 1871|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45212|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref> Gohmert said that \"conservatives have advocated for years that there should be no automatic spending increases in any federal department's budget... that has been a trap so when we simply slow the rate of increase, we are accused of making draconian cuts.\"<ref name=GohmertPRMay9>{{cite web|title=Gohmert Praises Baseline Reform Act of 2013|url=http://gohmert.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=333177|publisher=The Office of Congressman Louie Gohmert|accessdate=7 April 2014|date=May 9, 2013}}</ref> Gohmert argued that this legislation would make clearer \"what is an increase and what is a cut,\" put the government in the same situation as American families (who do not get automatic increases), and help with the task of getting the debt under control.<ref name=\"GohmertPRMay9\"/>\n\n====Social policy====\nGohmert has a pro-life voting record. He has stated that he believes that life begins at conception. Gohmert sponsored the Sanctity of Human Life Act. Gohmert voted for the Child Interstate Abortion Notification Act, a bill that prohibits the transportation of a minor across state lines for the purposes of an abortion without the consent of the minor's parents. He has 100% pro-life voting record rating from the [[NRLC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/TX/Louie_Gohmert.htm#Foreign_Policy |title=Louie Gohmert on Foreign Policy |publisher=OnTheIssues |accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepoliticalguide.com/rep_bios.php?rep_id=31558116&category=views&id=20100506100929 |title=Louie Gohmert&nbsp;\u2013 Abortion |publisher=The Political Guide |date= |accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt a congressional hearing on May 23, 2013, on an abortion bill that would ban the procedure after 20 weeks of pregnancy, Gohmert told the story of another couple he knew that decided to go through with their pregnancy despite learning of fetal anomalies. He told Zink, a woman witness, that she should have gone through with her pregnancy despite some doctor's opinion that the brain function was impaired, and then have a better assessment of the baby's health once it was born. Gohmert explained: \"Ms. Zink, having my great sympathy and empathy both, I still come back wondering, shouldn\u2019t we wait, like that couple did, and see if the child can survive before we decide to rip him apart? ... So these are ethical issues, they're moral issues, they\u2019re difficult issues, and the parents should certainly be consulted. But it just seems like, it\u2019s a more educated decision if the child is in front of you to make those decisions\", Gohmert said.<ref>{{cite news|title=Louie Gohmert Tells Woman She Should Have Carried Brain-Dead Fetus To Term, Just In Case (VIDEO)|author=Bassett, L.|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/24/louie-gohmert-abortion-ban_n_3332823.html|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=May 24, 2013|accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2012, two days after the murder of more than twenty people at an [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting|elementary school]], Gohmert appeared on [[Fox News Sunday]] and suggested that the tragedy would have never happened had the teachers been armed. He told host [[Chris Wallace]], \"I wish to God that she [principal Dawn L. Hochsprung] had had an [[M-4 carbine|M-4]] in her office, locked up so when she heard gunfire, she pulls it out... and takes him out and takes his head off before he can kill those precious kids.\" He claimed that the 20 victims who had been killed with a [[Bushmaster Firearms International|Bushmaster]] semi-automatic rifle had \"defensive wounds\".<ref>{{cite interview|last1=Lieberman|first1=J.|last2=Durbin|first2=D.|last3=Gohmert|first3=L.|interviewer=Wallace, C.|title=Connecticut school shooting reignites gun control debate; Gun policy|url=http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/fox-news-sunday-chris-wallace/2012/12/16/connecticut-school-shooting-reignites-gun-control-debate#p//v/2039381272001|format=News|program=Fox News Sunday|city=Washington, D. C.|date=December 16, 2012|accessdate=December 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====\"Terror baby\" national security vulnerability====\nOn August 12, 2010, Gohmert appeared on ''[[Anderson Cooper 360\u00b0]]'' to defend recent comments he made on the floor of the House regarding \"terror babies\". In a speech about national security made on the House floor in June 2010,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Video|title=Original speech|newspaper=Youtube|date=August 14, 2010|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_detailpage&v=dorCLFVpzyo|accessdate=August 14, 2010}}</ref> Gohmert stated that a retired FBI agent had told him that one of the things the FBI had been looking at were terrorist cells overseas sending young women to become pregnant so they would deliver the baby in the United States, and then take the baby with them back to be raised as a terrorist. When adult, this operative\u2014a U.S. citizen by birth\u2014could be easily infiltrated in the U.S. to carry out terrorist actions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/texas-rep-louie-gohmert-warns-baby-making-terrorists-coming-article-1.182787|title=Texas Rep. Louie Gohmert warns of baby-making terrorists coming to US|author=Joe Tapocino|publisher=nydailynews.com|date=June 27, 2010|location=New York}}</ref>\n\nOn Fox Business News, Gohmert later claimed that an airline passenger with a relative in [[Hamas]] had a grandchild who was to be intentionally born in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|title=... and avoid crackpot theories, too|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=August 14, 2010|url=http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/editorial_opinion/editorials/articles/2010/08/14/and_avoid_crackpot_theories_too|accessdate=August 14, 2010}}</ref> In the interview, Gohmert asserted that pregnant women from the Middle East are traveling to the US on tourist visas, planning to deliver the child there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texastribune.org/2010/06/28/tx-rep-louie-gohmert-warns-of-terrorist-babies|title=TX Rep. Louie Gohmert Warns of Terrorist Babies|author=Elise Hu|publisher=''[[The Texas Tribune]]''|date=June 28, 2010}}</ref> According to the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]], this automatically grants citizenship to the child. He said that the child would then be returned to the mother's home country and be submitted to a life of terrorist training. Rep. Gohmert said he could not reveal the identity of the retired FBI agent who provided him the information, but he pointed out to a ''[[The Washington Post]]'' article,<ref>{{Citation|last1=Richburg|first1=Keith|title=For many pregnant Chinese, a U.S. passport for baby remains a powerful lure|newspaper=Washington Post|date=July 18, 2010|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/17/AR2010071701402.html|accessdate=August 13, 2010}}</ref> which described \"[[birth tourism]]\" packages, mainly directed at Chinese tourists. These \"[[birth tourism]]\" packages, Gohmert pointed out, take advantage of a \"gaping hole in the security of our country.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Cooper|first=Anderson|authorlink=Anderson Cooper|title=Video: Rep. Gohmert on 'terror babies' conspiracy|work=CNN|date=August 12, 2010|url=http://ac360.blogs.cnn.com/2010/08/12/video-rep-gohmert-on-terror-babies-conspiracy|accessdate=August 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====Letter To Director Of National Intelligence====\nOn June 13, 2012, Gohmert was one of five Republican [[United States representative]]s (including [[Michele Bachmann]], [[Trent Franks]], [[Tom Rooney (politician)|Tom Rooney]], [[Lynn Westmoreland]]) to send letters to the Inspectors General<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.cmgdigital.com/shared/news/documents/2012/07/18/ig_letter_odni.pdf|title=House Members Seek National Security Answers|date=June 13, 2012|publisher=Congress of the United States|accessdate=August 23, 2012}}</ref> of the Office of the Director of National Intelligence, the Department of Defense, the Department of Homeland Security, the Department of Justice and the Department of State outlining their \"serious national security concerns\", and asking for \"answers to questions regarding the [[Muslim Brotherhood]] and other radical group's access to top Obama administration officials.\" In the letter, Gohmert and the other U.S. lawmakers wrote about information they claim \"raises serious questions about Department of State policies and activities that appear to be a result of influence operations conducted by individuals and organizations associated with the [[Muslim Brotherhood]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/238721-bachmann-responds-to-mccain-speech-the-letter-is-being-distorted|title=House Members Letter|date=July 18, 2012|publisher=The Hill|accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOne of the letters in particular to Ambassador Harold W. Geisel, the Deputy [[Inspector General]] of the [[United States Department of State]], mentioned the Deputy [[Chief of Staff]] to [[Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]], [[Huma Abedin]], as an example of the undue influence. The letter said that Abedin, wife of former U.S. representative [[Anthony Weiner]], who had access to sensitive national security and policy information, \"has three family members\u2013her late father, her mother and her brother\u2013connected to Muslim Brotherhood operatives and/or organizations\", as backed up by a study by the [[Center for Security Policy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://s3.documentcloud.org/documents/402379/rep-michele-bachmann-correspondence.pdf|title=Letter to the Ambassador Harold W. Geisel|date=June 13, 2012|format=PDF|publisher=Congress of the United States|accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cordes|first=Nancy|title=Michele Bachmann refuses to back down on claims about Huma Abedin|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-505267_162-57475483/michelle-bachmann-refuses-to-back-down-on-claims-about-huma-abedin/|accessdate=July 19, 2012|newspaper=CBS This Morning|date=July 19, 2012|quote=Bachmann, from Minnesota, and the four other representatives sent letters to top intelligence and security officials last week warning that the Muslim Brotherhood, a global religious Islamic movement whose members have been linked to terrorist groups in the past, may have infiltrated the top levels of U.S. government.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://muslimbrotherhoodinamerica.com/key-findings|title=Key Findings|last=Gaffney|first=Frank|work=The Muslim Brotherhood in America|publisher=Center for Security Policy|accessdate=August 11, 2012|quote=Notably, six Islamist-sympathizers have achieved positions within or advisory roles serving Team Obama: Special Envoy to the Organization of Islamic Cooperation Rashad Hussein; Deputy Chief of Staff to Secretary of State Hillary Clinton [[Huma Abedin]]; Presidential advisor Dalia Mogahed; FBI Citizens Academy graduate Kifah Mustafa; Homeland Security Advisory Committee Member [[Mohamed Elibiary]] and Homeland Security Countering Violent Extremism Working Group Member Mohamed Magid.}}</ref>\n\nGohmert and his colleagues were praised by [[Newt Gingrich]] as the \"National Security Five\" in an editorial on the [[Politico]] website. Gingrich expressed he favors investigating the Muslim Brotherhood, and made clear his support to Gohmert and the other four state-elected representatives for rising up concerns that improve national security.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0712/79104.html|title=In defense of Michele Bachmann, Muslim Brotherhood probes|author=Gingrich, Newt|date=July 29, 2012|work=Opinion Contributor|publisher=Politico|accessdate=August 11, 2012|quote=The underlying driving force behind this desperate desire to stop unpleasant questions is the elite\u2019s fear that an honest discussion of radical Islamism will spin out of control. They fear if Americans fully understood how serious radical Islamists are, they would demand a more confrontational strategy.}}</ref> Columnist [[Cal Thomas]] replied, to accusations of \"McCarthyism\", that the real possibility of infiltration by Islamic extremists deserves to be investigated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suppose Michele Bachmann is right?|first=Cal|last=Thomas|url=http://www.thestate.com/2012/07/29/2371334/thomas-suppose-michele-bachmann.html|newspaper=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]|date=July 29, 2012|accessdate=August 11, 2012|quote=Like the ghosts of Shakespeare's Banquo or Dickens' Jacob Marley, the specter of the late commie-hunting congressman from Wisconsin, [[Joseph McCarthy]], will always be with us. It is summoned up today, by some on the left, who use it as a tool to thwart legitimate questions about people and ideologies that seek to destroy America.}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n'''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n*[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on the Constitution, Civil Rights, and Civil Liberties|Subcommittee on the Constitution, Civil Rights, and Civil Liberties]]\n*[[United States House Judiciary Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security|Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security]]\n*[[United States House Judiciary Task Force on Judicial Impeachment|Task Force on Judicial Impeachment]]\n'''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n*[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources|Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources]]\n*[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands|Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands]]\n* Member, [[Republican Study Committee]] \n* Member, [[Tea Party Caucus]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*[[Israel Allies Caucus]]\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n*[[Tea Party Caucus]]\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin|title=[[Texas' 1st congressional district election, 2004]]<ref name=electionresults >{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist.exe|title=Certified Election Results|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=June 30, 2013}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (United States)|candidate=Louie Gohmert|votes=157,068|percentage=61.47%|change=}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=[[Max Sandlin]] (incumbent)|votes=96,281|percentage=37.68%|change=}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Libertarian Party (United States)|candidate=Dean L. Tucker|votes=2,158|percentage=0.84%|change=}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=[[Texas' 1st congressional district election, 2006]]<ref name=electionresults />}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (United States)|candidate=Louie Gohmert (incumbent)|votes=104,099|percentage=68.00%|change=}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=Roger L. Owen|votes=46,303|percentage=30.24%|change=}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Libertarian Party (United States)|candidate=Donald Perkison|votes=2,668|percentage=1.74%|change=}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=[[Texas' 1st congressional district election, 2008]]<ref name=electionresults/>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (United States)|candidate=Louie Gohmert (incumbent)|votes=189,012|percentage=87.57%|change=}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Independent (politician)|candidate=Roger L. Owen|votes=26,814|percentage=12.42%|change=}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=[[Texas' 1st congressional district election, 2010]]<ref name=electionresults/>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (United States)|candidate=Louie Gohmert (incumbent)|votes=129,398|percentage=89.72%|change=}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Libertarian Party (United States)|candidate=Charles F. Parkes III|votes=14,811|percentage=10.27%|change=}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=[[Texas' 1st congressional district election, 2012]]<ref name=electionresults/>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (United States)|candidate=Louie Gohmert (incumbent)|votes=178,322|percentage=71.4%|change=}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=Shirley J. Mckellar|votes=67,222|percentage=26.9%|change=}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Libertarian Party (United States)|candidate=Clark Patterson|votes=4,114|percentage=1.64%|change=}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nGohmert and his wife Kathy are parents to three daughters. Gohmert attends [[Green Acres Baptist Church]] in Tyler, where he has served as a deacon and teaches Sunday school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gohmert.house.gov/Biography/ |title=Biography: U.S. Congressman Louie Gohmert |publisher=Gohmert.house.gov |accessdate=April 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://gohmert.house.gov/ Congressman Louis Gohmert] official congressional website\n* [http://www.gohmert.com/ Louie Gohmert for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Louie_Gohmert_%5BR-1%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = G000552 | ballot = Louie_Gohmert | nndb = 128/000086867 | votesmart = 50029 | govtrack = 400651 | opencong = 400651_Louis_Gohmert | rollcall = 19262 | polit